 considering the metadata for the Class.forName target. I wonder if the call site is part of reachable code. It looks like the coverage report runs a Gradle task that analyzes Jacoco exec vs. native-image dynamic calls, marking lines covered by Jacoco. I suspect line 80 for class$ might not be covered. There are questions about whether Jacoco filters synthetic methods and if I should check existing Jacoco XML. The user mentioned not running it, but reading the old report could still be helpful.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_ViFcIaN0lUhyYwyDCAPgSszo|fc_0311e6f268442dbc0169f528104f4c819eb41f07f23e4ae220\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"rg \\\"TagSupport\\\" -n tests/src/jspapi/jsp-api/2.0-20040521/build/reports/jacoco/test/jacocoTestReport.xml | head -20\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 3969, \"output\": 724, \"cacheRead\": 21504, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 26197, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777674241915, \"responseId\": \"resp_0311e6f268442dbc0169f528025d1c819ea470f9ae9f7a6660\"}, \"toolResults\": [{\"role\": \"toolResult\", \"toolCallId\": \"call_ViFcIaN0lUhyYwyDCAPgSszo|fc_0311e6f268442dbc0169f528104f4c819eb41f07f23e4ae220\", \"toolName\": \"bash\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"(no output)\\n\\n[Showing lines 2-2 of 2 (50.0KB limit). Full output: /tmp/pi-bash-d3e7e0f4ee70bc44.log]\"}], \"details\": {\"truncation\": {\"content\": \"\", \"truncated\": true, \"truncatedBy\": \"bytes\", \"totalLines\": 2, \"totalBytes\": 89857, \"outputLines\": 1, \"outputBytes\": 0, \"lastLinePartial\": false, \"firstLineExceedsLimit\": false, \"maxLines\": 2000, \"maxBytes\": 51200}, \"fullOutputPath\": \"/tmp/pi-bash-d3e7e0f4ee70bc44.log\"}, \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777674256698}]}\n2857:[thinking] **Analyzing coverage reports**\n2859:[thinking] I'm looking at an old report regarding TagSupport, and I notice line 80 is missing from the source file, even though it's referenced. It seems like the JaCoCo coverage tool might be filtering out synthetic methods, which would explain the discrepancy. If JaCoCo doesn’t record class$ methods, that could cause dynamic coverage mapping issues since my task expects tests to reach that call site. This might require generating metadata based on the agent's actual output, not just the line coverage.\n2863:[thinking] I’m thinking about how the agent records reflection usage only when methods or constructors are actively accessed, rather than just with Class.forName on its own. So, maybe dynamic access reporting is false because the agent output doesn’t include \"javax.servlet.jsp.tagext.Tag\"? I need to inspect the agent output to see what it’s capturing. If Class.forName doesn’t require metadata, that might explain why it’s not being reflected in the reports. Let's dig into this!\n2869:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Analyzing coverage reports**\\n\\nI'm looking at an old report regarding TagSupport, and I notice line 80 is missing from the source file, even though it's referenced. It seems like the JaCoCo coverage tool might be filtering out synthetic methods, which would explain the discrepancy. If JaCoCo doesn’t record class$ methods, that could cause dynamic coverage mapping issues since my task expects tests to reach that call site. This might require generating metadata based on the agent's actual output, not just the line coverage.\\n\\n**Examining reflective access**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how the agent records reflection usage only when methods or constructors are actively accessed, rather than just with Class.forName on its own. So, maybe dynamic access reporting is false because the agent output doesn’t include \\\"javax.servlet.jsp.tagext.T